  "proof_sketch": "In compute_mean_var_kernel, the removal of __syncthreads() after initial writes to shared memory creates a data race. The reduction loop (stride = 128) reads shared_sum[tid + stride] without any preceding barrier. If the writing thread (tid+128) has not yet committed its write, the reading thread may see stale (uninitialized) data, yielding an incorrect sum. This directly affects the computed mean and variance, and thus the final output differs from the original barrier-protected version.",
  "survival_reason": "All prior tests used random or structured value distributions that did not guarantee that the race condition would manifest. Because the race is timing-dependent, many seeds randomly avoided the critical ordering. However, a uniform constant input (e.g., all ones) makes the race especially pernicious: each thread’s partial sum is a known constant, and any stale read from a different thread will cause a detectable deviation. The missing __syncthreads() is not redundant; the first reduction iteration reads cross-warp data without synchronization, so the mutant remains killable under the fixed-shape contract.",
  "killable": true,
  "kill_strategy": "Supply an input where every element is the same constant (e.g., 1.0). This makes the correct per-feature sum trivially computable, and any race-induced error (e.g., reading uninitialized shared memory or a stale zero) will produce a different result.",
  "suggested_test": {
    "description": "Uniform constant input to expose the shared-memory data race in compute_mean_var_kernel",
